If you need a target, try the Seej basic bloxen: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:23620 Seej is a tabletop wargame based around 3D printing. ReplicatorG is pretty forgiving, but other slicing software may be less so. EDIT 6/30/12: I've uploaded wee_ballista.stl for users still having issues with the size of their build platforms. LOOK HERE FOR NEW UPDATED AND ACTUALLY PRINTED 1x2x3: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2731582

My 1x2x3

Another 1x2x3, but a good one at that. I built this puzzle as a base model for all my future 1x2x3 mods (1x2x3 2x2x3 mashup, square-1x2x3, etc), but it's not just any old 1x2x3. The design has center supports which make it much more stable than average 1x2x3s and it has sliding caps that are hidden after you put the stickers on.

Print:

  • 1 x Center-1
  • 1 x Center-2
  • 4 x Corner
  • 2 x Cap

Assembly

First, slide all the corner pieces into the centers. To assemble the cores you will need one M3 screw and nut as well as a spring. Put the nut in the center with the hexagonal hole. Put the spring on the screw and put it through the other centerpiece. Screw the screw in the nut. :l rather simple. Slide the two caps in and apply stickers to secure them in place. And that's it, folks!

Disclaimer

Ok, I do realize that there are TONS of 1x2x3s, but I thought I should upload this model anyhow seeing that I made it and maybe, just maybe, someone can benefit from it. Also, I need more stuff in my portfolio.

Also, this puzzle is built with zero tolerance meaning that there is no space between the pieces. You will probably need to do a little sanding to get the pieces just right.

description.text:
Other materials required:

  • 30 5mm blue or white LEDs
    • You won't need all 30 but that gives room for duds
  • 100 ohm resistors (1 for each LED)
  • 24 gauge copper wire
  • An old USB cord
  • 3 M2 x 20mm bolts

Remix changes

  • Entire model shrunk to 80% of original size
  • Crystal Ring and Main Crystal modified to fit 5mm LEDs after shrinking
  • Caps shrunk to 77% of original size to keep a tighter fit
  • Support cage:
    • Modified to fit 5mm LEDs
    • Fillets applied at the base of the top arms to prevent them from snapping off
    • Fillets applied to the top of the top arms to help them insert into the Crystal ring easier
  • Hole size increased on Main crystal, Lower center, and Upper center to fit m2 x 20 screws

Notes:
  • Print the support cage at 100% infill
  • Crystals can be done in translucent or white filament. Play with the infill density and type to get the desired lighting. I used 30% infill on translucent filament with a cubic subdivision pattern.

Wiring

After printing, LEDs need to be inserted into the crystal ring and the support cage. Add hot glue under the LEDs in the support cage to keep them in (shown in photos). LEDs should be wired in parallel and each LED should have a resistor. It does not matter if the resistor is on the anode or the diode. Copper wire can be threaded through the support cage to connect the ring LEDs with the ones in the support cage.

For the USB cable, cut off the other end (I used a micro USB cable), and you should see 4 wires. Cut down the ones that are not red and black. The red and black ones are power and ground, respectively. Wire those directly to your circuit.

Assembly

Wrap copper wire around the caps, and use super glue at the ends. After the glue has dried, use wire cutters to trim the bottom so that they can be placed over the Crystal Ring.

Push the caps onto the crystal ring until they are all the way down. Push the crystal ring onto the support cage while threading the power and ground leads through the arms (see photo). Make sure the LEDs are trimmed short enough that they don't interfere with putting the crystal on the support cage.

Screw together the Main crystal, Lower center, and Upper center with the M2 screws. They will be very tight on the first time. Just screw them in with a handheld screwdriver. Once done, push the whole assembly into the support cage. The LEDs in the support cage should have a tight enough fit to the main crystal to hold it all in.

Run the USB cable through the Back Cap and solder it to the wiring on the bottom of the support cage. Slide the Back Cap up and hot glue it to the support cage.

LEDs not fitting?

If you are printing on a heated build platform, sometimes the bottom layer ends up expanding a little bit because it is slightly soft. This ends up making the holes for the LEDs slightly smaller than they should be. To verify if this is the problem, insert the LED from the other side and see if it fits. To fix this, trim the edges of the holes on the bottom layer with an exacto blade. The LEDs should just press in tightly, and stay without glue.

If you see that copper wire that threads through the support cage, one of those wires is power and one is ground. Doesn't matter which. So you connect those to ground/power on the ring, and then also connect them to ground/power on the LEDs in the support cage. The USB cable has ground/power as well, so you just wire that to the copper wires as well. I don't have a picture, but I did power/ground on the support cage LEDs in a similar way to the ring. I just wrapped ground around one half of the circle, and power around the other half. You may need to get creative in how you place the resistors. It was a pretty tight fit and took some trial and error.

I recommend setting your slicer software to print "inside out" to make sure the curved edges of the frames and the nubs that hold the earpieces to the face print properly without sagging.

I used a piece of curved cardboard and a heat gun to lightly curve the face of the frames. I also heated up the earpieces and pressed them to the outside of my reading glass earpieces so they would have the same standard shape. Make sure to let them cool enough before setting them down.

And also be careful with a heat gun, they can cause serious burns on your fingers if you get them too close. I used a pair of pliers to hold the pieces when heating them up. Also I recommend using a piece of tile to place the pieces on while using the heat gun. Ceramic tile will help dissipate the heat and prevent you from burning your tabletop.

This is a TronXY base that can be printed in small pieces on the actual TronXY. I was inspired by the other bases available. I did however want to be able to print it 100% on the TronXY X1 with NO MODS. I also wanted it in smaller pieces just in case something goes wrong. Another big plus is you can customize the parts really easily with your logos and designs or extra holes. They are mostly flat panels with only the required holes, no big names or lettering added so you can just add whatever you want.

All source files included (DWG for autocad 2010+, DXF for Autocad 2007+ and whatever else you can import it into.

The biggest pieces are the bottom pieces (140x140mm). If you don't have your printer tuned for this size you could just skip the base and cut it from cardboard or whatever else you have on hand. The biggest side-piece is 120mm long and the case will work 100% without the bottom if you glue the sides together.

Notes:
  • Make sure you have a properly leveled bed before printing. These are flat parts so they will be very dependent on having a reasonably leveled bed.
  • The only part that MAY need supports is the 'rounded corner'. This is the only part that I printed upright and I managed to get it done without any supports. I just cut off the crappy parts under the overhangs.

Mounting the pieces together

You can glue these together with superglue/epoxy/UHU or whatever. I just press-fit mine and just dabbed some super-glue on the joints and they held up well.

There are no tolerances included on the joints, they are intended to be lightly SANDED or FILED before being press-fit together. Mine went together without much issues. The base has 2mm of tolerance in the grooves the sides slot into, so even if it's not perfect it should still fit together.

You can also fit the whole power brick INSIDE if you so desire, there is ample room.

Designed in Autocad

All source files are included, you can use them with any software that can load up an Autocad DWG or generic DXF file. This is so you can add text or designs or whatever you wish to the panels.

description.text: This one works

Did your printrbot come with a P-block for the bed without an endstop mount? Did your printrbot come with the old style hotbed carriage without the integrated endstop mount? My original hotbed carriage stop cracked very quickly, and mine never had a y-stop. So i made these up, and tested them, and they are now on my printer.

Print these parts. NOTE you might have to file off the corner of the right x-carriage holder, otherwise the screw might hit it during printing... check clearance before printing anything.
To install y-stop, take the nut off the corner of the bed which has the y-stop microswitch on it, put the y-stop mount on the bed screw, and slide/screw it on, replace nut. Then screw an extra screw from your kit (or one of the same size) of an appropriate length into the hole, and set the y-stop position.
For the x-stop, unscrew the upper screw that attaches the hotend to the x carriage, remove the cracked/broken one the kit came with if present, and screw the new piece in, adding a screw to the hole and set the x-stop position.

description.text:
UPDATED! Open cable chain links and clip. Clip design adapted from schnuffi's design and slapped onto my thinned variation of the cable chain by sukhoi27

I included the X Axis extruder end and motor mount by The_Random_Engineer which I plan on tweeking in a later date.

Thinning the cable chain made by sukhoi27 and chamfering the inner chain edge for ease of assembly. I also cleaned up the Y-Bed bracket of unnecessary geometry and thinned the wall to fit the profile of my chain.

I mounted it to my Anet A8 using M4.7x12mm screws and nuts. Though the nuts probably weren't needed and you may be able to get away without using screws like Papinist did with his thinned bracket design. I just like it sturdy.

I also added holes to the Y-Bed bracket to accommodate a zip tie to act as a strain relief for the wires which I soldered directly to the board (14ga.). Holding them in place securely.

P.S. After installation I started hearing squeaking. After much searching and fear of bad bearings, I found out it was the cable chain. So if you too hear squeaking check to see if it is the cable chain before you freak out!

P.P.S On the subject of the X-Axis motor mount my Anet's hex screws were too short to reach the motor through its mount and that bracket. I used the longer Phillips screws that came with my printer and carved out the lower screw hole so that the standard hex screw would just slide into the hole no problem. I plan on reworking the design as such and shortening the Z-axis adjustment screw bracket. Currently, you'll need a longer screw and to tap the hole for an M3 screw or as I did just work the screw in and it'll carve the threads itself but that is difficult.

description.text:
Watch Zeldathon Wild this June 5-11!

Here's a collectable shield, made for this event.

The small handles on the back should allow you to wear this shield on a chain, or hang it on a wall with a piece of string.

If you enjoy this design, please make a donation to Zeldathon! Please mention where you came from in the comments. If you're not sure how much to give, I recommend $3.00 as a good starting point. (Or $3.14 if you're nerdy.)

Notes:

Sliced with Slic3r, printed in silver PLA. Using 100% infill gives it a higher-quality feel.

If you're using Fleks3D, or similarly have really good platform adhesion, no supports should be required when printing with the flat top touching the build platform (see photos). A raft is still recommended.

Without supports, the print tends to get a little squirrely towards the bottom of the shield. Since Breath of the Wild is about a Hyrule in ruins, I think this gives it some extra personality!

This design was made in OpenSCAD.

The fonts used are Hylia Serif Beta and Helvetica Neue (Bold).

The Master Sword outline was made from scratch in Pixelmator.

The Triforce is made by subtracting a rotated cylinder of diameter D from a cylinder with diameter 2D... both cylinders are rendered with a "number of fragments" of 3, which reduces them to triangular prisms.

description.text:
So... This is my problem!

I don't like the grass collected in my Quadcopter when it lands, so I have been wanting to find a surround to fill the gaps, I also wanted to include space for my Eachine TVL1000 fpv camera as it is quite large for this size quad, and has a very wide angled lens. and finally, I wanted to find a way for the GPS to be outside the carbon fibre and visible to the sky.

I think I have managed to do ok - just need to wait for an opportunity to fly. Probably the colur I've printed in is not best for grass stains - but it will keep the grass out of the electronics! also, may be easier to find when crashed!

I'd like to shout out thanks to MRRacequad for inspiration, he has a great design. but for my set up, there would be too many changes to make, so rather than remix, I've designed my own, using a ruler, pen, paper and Sketchup.

It's a first attempt, so 'it worked for me' but still is a work in progress.

description.text:
Stand for smartphone to record timelapse videos of 3D prints. A video/timelapse recording app is required. It is placed on the hot bed and records the video always from the same plane, so that in the timelapse the whole construction is recorded perfectly.

For mobiles up to 1.8 cm thick. It is recommended to put on the protector a self-adhesive felt, like the furniture pads, to protect the mobile screen.

A 30mm screw with 3mm of diameter is required, with its corresponding nut.

A light and a heavy clamp frame is provided. The light version is more than enough to hold the mobile phone firmly.

The best way to mount the protector is to use the clamp itself by closing the clamp until the screw ball and protector joint clicks together.

To record videos on Android you can use, for example, the Framelapse app.

description.text:
SKATEFORCE. Wall mount to hang electric longboards for Press Reset's challenge.

Goals:
1: You must post your design to Thingiverse by midnight EST June 6th.
2: You can enter as many times as you like, but try to be reasonable LOL
3: Your bracket MUST be a SINGLE print design, not multi part.
4: The design must NOT use any supports.
5: You can support the deck, wheels or the trucks, it can be horizontal or vertical.
6: Your design can NOT be a remix of another design, it MUST be original.
7: You can use whatever design software you want, but you must provide a downloadable STL as the final output.
8: You must tag your file on Thingiverse with #SKATEFORCE in the title and in the description.
9: You must place the YouTube link to this video in the description.

Video link in description:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pVH-GfD4Sfo

No

Notes:

Took 28 hours to print the main bracket.

Printed with Maker Geek Royal Purple PLA.

Wall mount

The three screw holes are not so much for strength (two is sufficient) but more for alignment with studs or to improve placement option. The covers can be printed as the singles, Press Reset Dual/Single Extrusion Panel, Blank/Custom panel. While gauged for the wider longboard trucks it fit my regular skateboard (with 80mm wheels and 1/2 inch riser) just fine.

Unfortunately the footage I took of my self standing on the bracket was poorly shot and was a great view of the packing crate. I did get a nice shot of my efforts to hop on the bracket repeatedly until it broke. I am 200lbs for reference. I would not recommend this for items over 50 lbs for safety. As not all printers and filament are created equal or parts made under similar conditions I cannot guarantee similar results, so please be careful.

Strength can be improved by heat treating or printing at a lower layer height but even with PLA this should be more than sufficient for an electric skateboard.

Stress Test

Measurements

Hardest part for me was figuring out how, well, anything dimension wise should be.

I started with my limiting factors:
-Printer, at this time I only have access to my office's Prusa i3 MK2. That's my max size.
-Boards. I don't own any long boards or electric boards but I could find out what is on the market. This set my range.

Looking at the boards they seemed to vary wildly, except in the front axel/truck. I focused on that as my basis to build from. Most vendors listed the truck and wheel size. With this information jotted down in my project notebook I moved onto designing.

This is a remix from "The Witness Dude" https://www.tinkercad.com/things/4JA0nvNWpfM created by the True Mike Brown.

The sculpture comes from the game The Witness, and can be found near the end of the game.

The original model from the game had numerous issues that kept it from printing cleanly. I've tried to fix as many of those issues as possible, and simplify the layout a bit.

  • removed floating puzzle symbols, replaced with (fewer) recreated symbols
  • fixed box not adhering to the floor tile below
  • removed original floor tile and replaced with tiles of varying thickness. This new flooring better connects with the bottom parts of the man, is stronger, and more tightly conforms to the outline of the sculpture
  • filled some holes in the man sculpture that resulted in infill being visible
  • added filler objects under the folded leg to reduce the amount of support material that had to be removed from a tight space.
  • added supports to both hands, the stylus, and connected the left elbow an knee. This should help keep the individual fingers from breaking off when supports are removed.

title: TEVO Little Monster Duet WiFi/Ethernet Conversion (With 7" PanelDue)

description.text:
This is a full set of instructions, models, and configuration files to convert a TEVO Little Monster from an MKS-SBASE controller and TFT-LCD to a Duet3D Duet Wifi/Ethernet controller with a 7" PanelDue LCD. NOTE: These instructions are for the latest and greatest Duet3D controllers (not version 0.8.5) and also assume you know how the Duet controller operates. For more information on basic operation of the Duet controller, please see the following link and run through the entire Getting Started section of the page:

https://duet3d.com/wiki/Duet_Wiki

Mounting the Duet3D controller:
The stock controller case will hold the new controller without any issues, but the mounting holes are completely different dimensions than the MKS-SBASE. When the front of the TEVO Little Monster is facing you, I used the front-left brass mounting post hole as my baseline for drilling and tapping three new holes for mounting the Duet3D controller. The Plexiglas face plate TEVO has installed on the controller case will not work with the Duet3D controller (you will have to design your own, which will make a great simple first print once you complete this conversion).

3D Models for the 7" PanelDue Case and Mount:
Top-15mm.stl - Created by EclecticAngler (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1992124) and is the main enclosure for the 7" PanelDue. After printing, the two tallest screw mounts on the model must be removed (just snap them off) or they will interfere with the latest PanelDue design.

LPA_TFT28BoxV3_FootM5.stl - Created by Elzariant (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2132557) and this is the mounting bracket that will allow you to attach the back cover to the TEVO Little Monster's stock LCD bracket mounting location.

Back_Cover.stl - This is the back cover I designed to mate the two other models together to create a complete mounting system for the 7" PanelDue.

Wiring:
BL-Touch to Duet Controller.txt - Instructions on how to wire up the BL-Touch to work properly with the Duet WiFi/Ethernet

Configuration:
config.zip - The enclosed configuration files are for a Duet Ethernet with DHCP enabled for network connectivity, but can be used with the following configuration tool to create the basic configuration settings for a Duet WiFi (I don't have a config.json for you to load into the tool, so you will have to manually enter the settings):

https://configurator.reprapfirmware.org/

If you do this to create the files for a Duet WiFi, make sure you include the enclosed deploy/retractprobe.g files in the ZIP file created by the configuration tool (the tool doesn't know how to configure the BL-Touch). You must also retain the G31 section in the enclosed config.g file (located in the config.zip file) in order to get things running properly.

The ZIP file can be uploaded directly to the Duet through DuetWebControl. Given my TEVO Little Monster was put together by me probably differs slightly in physical construction compared to yours, you will probably have to mess with the delta radius (the R variable in g-code command M665 located in config.g) as well as the Z-offset of the BL-Touch (the Z variable in g-code command G31 located in config.g).

bed.g:
You will have to reconfigure your slicer to run the bed.g prior to starting the print. You can do this by issuing the command M98 Pbed.g in a startup script. This will calibrate the bed prior to every print, which only takes a few seconds to complete. The script will call the deployprobe.g and retractprobe.g files to activate and deactivate the BL-Touch during the calibration process.

HUGE THANKS to the Duet3D team for designing a truly amazing printer controller, the Duet3D community for making a very comprehensive BL-Touch configuration thread (https://www.duet3d.com/forum/thread.php?id=459), the above listed designers for the parts that allowed me to get the 7" PanelDue securely attached to the TEVO Little Monster, and of course TEVO for designing great mechanics for the Little Monster!

Just make sure you test everything before you attempt to print. Work all of the axis, check to make sure the heaters work and the thermistors are reporting properly (I used an infrared temperature gun), and decrease the Z height so that when the machine attempts to calibrate using the BLTouch, it's actually trying to touch mid air. If your A8 is like mine, the Z calibrator is too short. It will disappear into the X Axis bearing assembly long before it engages and your Z Stop will get whacked. Rather than make a longer Calibrator and sacrifice Z axis, use two of these inserts to cap the calibration tool. Disable the motors, rotate the Z Axis down to just touch the insert, then re-enable the motors. Remove and store the inserts.

description.text:
I tried others design out there but cannot make it work for a 40mm of 11mm/16mm of thickness.

So after wasting PLA, I decided to make one that work with 40mm fan with thickness of max 16mm.

The bottom have m3 holes in a grid layout of 10mm between each holes. Should work fine for any design out there...

This thing come with 3 STL, one for the COVER, the 2 others are the enclosure for HOT BED and HOT END. The only difference between these 2 are the name on the box :).

I put the fan in outtake mode, so the hot air are suck outside, at the same time new air are coming from the vent holes.

Hope you like it.

description.text:
Basically, I wanted a cheap way to implement the nozzle clean feature of marlin/skynet. I had tried felt like the taz uses and it just was not holding up well. I found a cheap brass brush at Harbor Freight and modeled a mount for it that allows for easy changing of the brush head.

This Is ideal for an auto level setup and adjusting the springs will move the height of the brush. it can be done however as long as the z stop is adjusted so only the bristles protrude past the bed.

Update: 05/31/17
I've added two variants of the Brush Mount as the original was designed for 5MM glass beds. There are now a -2mm for 3MM glass beds and a -5MM for those using inductive sensors and printing on the aluminum bed.

Update: 06/01/17
Fixed Brush Mount -5MM - the mounting holes did not go all the way through the mount

https://youtu.be/Zb9W94K1ciM Video here.

The pieces slide together fairly tight. I added a M5 square nuts and M5x10 Button head screw to lock them into place but this is probably not necessary. you will need two slightly longer m4 screws to mount it to the H frame.

What you will need:
a Harbor freight brass brush https://www.harborfreight.com/1-3-8-eighth-inch-x-7-inch-brass-detail-brush-40441.html
Print the three pieces
Brush Shell - this just keeps the brush bristles tighter together.
Brush Bottom - the brush shell slides into the brush bottom.
Brush mount - this screws on top of the h frame where the bearings mount. The brush bottom slides onto this.
Two slightly longer M4 screws
M5 square nut (optional)
M5x10 button head socket screw (optional)
Marlin or skynet.

To set up:

//#define NOZZLE_CLEAN_FEATURE <------------ uncomment this line by removing the // <br/>
#if ENABLED(NOZZLE_CLEAN_FEATURE)
// Default number of pattern repetitions
#define NOZZLE_CLEAN_STROKES 12
// Default number of triangles
#define NOZZLE_CLEAN_TRIANGLES 5

// Specify positions as { X, Y, Z }
#define NOZZLE_CLEAN_START_POINT { -17, 122, (Z_MIN_POS + 1.5)}
#define NOZZLE_CLEAN_END_POINT {-9, 152, (Z_MIN_POS + 1.5)}

Set up your starting and ending positions for the brush by jogging to the bottom left corner and lowering your nozzle until its at a height you like. take now these coordinates then jog to the top right corner and do the same. input those numbers above.

now Just add the G12 command to your start code. I used G12 P1 S2 T7 P is pattern 0 is straight lines 1 is triangles and 2 is circles. S are how many strokes and T is how many triangles within the cleaning perimeter.

G28 ; Home All
G12 P1 S2 T7 ; Clean Nozzle
G29 ; Auto level

description.text:
This is a housing for SS40 or SS41 type Hall Effect Position Sensors. It will also work with other sensors using the same package style. These sensors use a small transistor like package that is difficult to mount. This housing allows the sensor to be soldered to the end of a 5 mm diameter cable and then slid into the housing and glued in place. The face where magnetic flux is applied pokes through a window in the face of the housing. Gluing the sensor in place is optional because the 5 mm cable should fit tight in the housing and hold the sensor into its pocket. A drop of glue or hot glue should be used to keep the 3 wires from shorting together before inserting the sensor into the housing. This housing can be printed in PLA or for harsh environments ABS or PETG can be used.

I often soften the edges of the sensor with 320 grit sandpaper so that the sensor can slide and snap into place inside the housing. Otherwise it can tend to hang up when sliding into place.

The completed sensor can be mounted with two 4-40 or 3 mm screws.

This sensor works with the MachTach machine tachometer.
